#X text 546 74 A simple way to set the depth range is with the [rescale~] object by setting the minimum aplitude. We simply subtract the depth from 1 \, which at 0 depth means a minimum and maximum value at 1 \, and a depth of 1 goes down to 0 (try other values in between)., f 66;
#X obj 263 380 *~;
#X obj 263 407 +~;
#X obj 334 379 clip 0 1;
#X obj 334 407 / 2;
#X obj 263 340 osc~ 1;
#X obj 334 462 expr 1 - $f1;
#X floatatom 334 434 7 0 0 0 - - - 0;
#X floatatom 334 490 9 0 0 0 - - - 0;
#X obj 337 332 hsl 128 15 0 1 0 0 empty empty empty -2 -8 0 10 #dcdcdc #000000 #000000 0 1;
#X text 383 331 Depth;
#X obj 334 355 nbx 5 14 -1e+37 1e+37 0 0 empty empty empty 0 -8 0 10 #dcdcdc #000000 #000000 0 256;
#X obj 263 477 vsl 20 100 0 1 0 0 empty empty empty 0 -9 0 10 #dcdcdc #000000 #000000 0 1;
#X text 288 569 0;
#X text 287 470 1;
#X obj 263 447 s2f~;
#X text 27 218 A proper Tremolo effect has a depth control \, which is a way to control the DC-Offset and gain. Below do it by setting the gain at half the depth value and the DC-offset to 1 minus that value. For instance \, a depth of 0.5 sets the gain to 0.25 (so it goes from -0.25 to 0.25) and the DC-Offset to 0.75 (so it goes from 0.5 to 1)., f 64;
#X obj 780 341 play.file~ bubul.mp3 1 1;
#X text 930 449 Depth;
#X obj 782 475 tremolo~ 10 1;
#X text 812 210 The [tremolo~] object is an abstraction that implements this process. Note how the tremolo effect is well suited for any kind of input and is a common guitar FX pedal., f 29;
